3. ut . . . superarit: (for superaverit) a result clause where an accus. and inf. would be more regular after verum est (G. 332 f ; Η. 501, Ι, 2).

3. infitiandum: prej udiced Romans might easily do this ; later several statues of Hannibal were set up at Rome.

4. ceteros: we should expect ceteris (dat.); see on omnes, p. 47, l. 7. In one tale Hannibal is represented as claiming only third place, putting Alexander the Great and Pyrrhus before himself.

6. antecedat: this is subjunct. by attraction from its depen- dence on the inf. praestitisse (G. 342 ; H. 529, II).

7. congressus est . . . discessit: sc. Hannibal for subject of these. Hannibal did meet with one repulse at the hands of Marcellus when he attacked Nola, a Campanian city, in 214. This was a mere trifle compared with the long list of Hannibal’s victories, but the Romans made a great deal of it.
